Can you consider what it would be like to have an internal room to go to that understands, soothes, nurtures, reassures, values and loves you when feelings of self-doubt or ‚ÄúI am not good enough‚Äù get triggered?

We each get caught in moments where we loose faith in ourselves, without understanding why. These are the times when the voice of self-questioning speaks.

We all have a version of ‚ÄúI am not enough‚Äù and the versions get really strong when we are being challenged.

We might push the voice aside by filling our lives with distractions or silence it when we get the job or the relationship or the thing that we think will make us ‚Äúenough‚Äù. Until we come to some juncture where we feel empty or deficient. It is this juncture that heralds a really important stage of growth.

We support this growth each time we practice connecting with ourselves in a place of presence. By choosing to live in a true and present self, we can catch and acknowledge these moments with a new awareness, where we can identify what is happening and regard a particular thought or feeling for what it really is, not for what we presume it is. We can ask with a sense of awareness what it is we are most afraid of, and if it is really true?

The more we practice, the more we invest in and strengthen our internal resources. It is like money in the bank of our emotional wellbeing - we fulfill ourselves on the inside.

If we keep clinging to familiar behavioural patterns and self-limiting beliefs about ourselves, we can never gift ourselves the opportunity to step into a larger, more wholehearted and truly authentic version of who we really are. 
Letting go of the self we think we need to be in order to be regarded can support us in updating our programme. This is a process that requires courage so we can trust ourselves enough to stand in our own humility, and humanity. It is from this compassionate place of felt presence and connection with ourselves where we connect with our hearts, that we can truly grow in the relationship with our self, and with others.

#honouringyourtrueself #vulnerability #humility #humanity #compassionate #presence #connection #relationships #lawofattraction

We can model intimacy by opening to our partner from a place of true and heartfelt connection with our internal experience. This can be the expression of feelings of love, acknowledgement and understanding, or disappointment, loss, and heartbreak. It is from this place of presence that we invite another heart to connect with ours. However, when we are met with distance, dismissiveness, or defensiveness, we cannot create or belong to an intimate space in this relationship. Rather than reacting to our experience of not being seen or acknowledged, we can allow our conscious selves to adopt a new understanding and compassion towards this other who is unable to meet us with an open heart. Thus, when we choose to occupy a conscious space within ourselves, we can discern and choose relationships where our emergence can be supported and nurtured.

#honouringyourtrueself #intimacy #connection #selflove #compassion

For example when we share with our partner our experience of: 
Hurt and disappointment when we perceive we are not considered or regarded properly. 
Love and regard when we are considered, appreciated, and valued.

This practice of connecting with our feelings and then expressing them in a wholehearted way requires us to turn away from habit, automatic reactions and roles. Instead, we give ourselves the space to respond in a present way to our interactions and emotional experiences as they unfold. In this way, we connect with our vulnerability. By responding from this place, we nurture an emotional connection in our relationships and we allow ourselves to be truly seen (In To Me See). When we dismiss, without question, uncomfortable, or difficult experiences in our relationships, we dismiss our needs and they remain unseen.

Moreover, by communicating our experience from a place of connection with our vulnerability, we help our partner to understand our needs and to see into us more. We also create the opportunity for our partner to respond. This is true maturity and intimacy in action. 
#honouringyourtrueself #intimacy #relationship #vulnerability #selfcompassion #connection #romanticlove #bevulnerable

My hope for 2020 is that I can stay compassionate, understanding and kind in times of difficulty and disappointment in my relationships. 
True relationships can allow for, and withstand, behaviour that is imperfect and human. However, when we turn and judge another for their imperfect humanity, or vice versa, then our relationship is not built from a place of trust or mutual regard. 
We are not always going to be aligned with other people‚Äôs belief systems, nor are they with ours. The secret is to know when we are viewing through an uncompromising lens.

Therefore observing other people‚Äôs behaviour with understanding as to where they are on their journey, and we on ours, allows us to experience these interactions without getting hooked. In this way, we can remain grounded and open to experiencing what is really at play in the here-and-now. 
#honouringyourtrueself #imperfect #humanity #kindness #understanding #compassion #relationshipgoals #intention #2020 #NewYear

At one stage or another, we each experience unexpected shifts in our relationships. Moreover, when there is no understanding of these sudden changes, we struggle to figure out how to respond. When we sense distance, we get carried away in the trance of the ‚Äústory‚Äù, whose narrative stems from a very narrow version of who we are and who we need to be in order to be valued and loved.

By scrutinizig our own beliefs about relationships; and who we need to be in order to be seen, valued and regarded; and who ‚Äúthe other‚Äù is, we bring to light the very subconscious, automatic and reactive behaviours we tend to adopt in relationships. These behaviours often yield very disconnecting results. For example, in our efforts to be considerate and regard the other, we inadvertently undermine our selves. 
However, rather than making excuses for others and discounting our own needs, we can instead learn to turn towards ourselves. When this can be done with understanding and self-love, we act with compassion towards ourselves. From this place, we acknowledge and accept our own emotional experience, we also see the other through much more present and compassionate eyes.

Setting an intention for Christmas üéÑ. I believe that it is hugely important that we keep an eye to caring for ourselves this Christmas. We can so easily trick ourselves into believing that in order to experience a meaningful Christmas we need to get busy, and say ‚Äúyes‚Äù to everyone and everything. All too easily we disconnect from our true selves.

The truth is that in order to experience meaning and connection with the world around us, we need to connect with ourselves first. This means acknowledging our needs with presence and compassion. Just as a really understanding and kind parent recognizes the child who needs to be cared for, we can seek to recognize our needs and care for ourselves. 
We support ourselves in doing this when we focus our minds on what is happening in the moment, right now without any sort of pressure to change it. By making simple observations such as noticing our breath, how our feet meet the floor or the position of our back against a chair, we can bring ourselves back into a feeling of presence and connection with ourselves. This is the practice of presence. It supports us in recognizing our behaviour so we can respond consciously to it. This can simply mean saying to ourselves, ‚ÄúI know you think you need to be doing this, but you are tired / under pressure and not honouring what you really need to give to yourself now.‚Äù Sometimes this might mean saying ‚Äúno‚Äù to someone or something or responding with care and compassion when we are reminded of our imperfect humanity. 
Each time we support ourselves in this way, we choose to meet ourselves. From this place of connection with our true selves, we can experience meaning and connection with the world around us. This is my intention for Christmas, to connect with myself with acceptance and understanding, and to connect with others.

#honouringyourtrueself 
#christmas2019 #selfcompassion #presence #understanding #kindness #intention

Do you feel unseen and unloved in your relationships? 
I wrote #HonouringYourTrueSelf because I wanted to offer readers the tools and resources that can support mutually caring relationships. With each step along this path, I nudge the reader in directions that previously may never have been considered or explored. In particular, I bring to the foreground our automatic behavioural patterns and belief systems surrounding relationships, and how we can adjust these to align with our true selves. 
#HonouringYourTrueSelf  https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1697903746/

Disregarding our vulnerability is often part of living out of our unconscious script, which is based on idealisations about who we are supposed to be in our relationships, and who others are supposed to be. We react by pressurising ourselves to conform to a life we think we are supposed to live, where we try to mould ourselves into shapes that do not truly fit and act in ways that we think are expected of us. When we try to meet other people‚Äôs expectations of us, we struggle to become our true selves. So when we feel isolated and disappointed, we pretend we are fine. We think showing strength means disregarding our vulnerability, when the opposite is the truth. Sometimes we lose faith in ourselves and settle for relationships, when deep down we know we are not honouring our true, authentic selves. Why do we do this? This is what I explore in #honouringyourtrueself

#lawsofattraction #compassion #selflove #vulnerabilityisstrength

I used to believe that it was easier to quash uncomfortable feelings and run from them. Until I realized that our feelings and emotions are the ingredients for mutually caring and supportive relationships. Vulnerability is the gateway to connection. Therefore, each time we honour our feelings including our fears, disappointments, loss and loneliness, we honour our true self and we show up in our relationships. 
However, when we have been coached to believe that feelings need to be shunned, we run from ourselves. Consequently, any chance of developing a wholehearted connection in our relationships is lost.

Moreover, when we subconsciously sign a contract with ourselves where we withhold and ultimately disregard our feelings, we step into a much narrower version of ourselves where we begin to focus on negative aspects of our relationships, which is usually some version of ‚ÄúI am not good enough‚Äù or ‚Äúyou are not good enough‚Äù. So how can we move away from reactive behaviours where feelings are automatically shunned, and instead move towards responsive behaviours where we consciously acknowledge and allow our feelings? 
Compassion can provide the opening to a new groove that can support us in connecting emotionally with our self first and foremost, and then with others. We develop this practice when we choose to see ourselves as our most valued and cherished friend. 
Each time we look to ourselves with understanding and love, we honour our experience and we learn to acknowledge, hold and nurture our uncomfortable feelings with compassion. By choosing to honour our experience in this heartfelt way, we show up for ourselves. When we express ourselves from this place of heart connection in our relationships we allow ourselves to be truly seen. We also choose to truly see ‚Äúthe other‚Äù. #honouringyourtrueself #compassion #selfcare #love #relationshipgoals #relationships #connection #emotionalconnection #romanticlove

I wanted to say a proper hello to my followers and tell you a bit more about me. My name is Evie, I am the author of ‚ÄúHonouring Your True Self‚Äù, a book I wrote to help people who feel unseen and loved in their relationships, to develop more satisfying, loving and deeply fulfilling relationships.

How did I arrive at this station?
Well, I used to believe that I never held back in life. I always strived to give myself the very best opportunities, the best qualifications‚Ä¶the best everything.

However, the reality is that I held back all the time, I just didn‚Äôt realise it. When it came to relationships, I allowed them to happen to me. Moreover, I didn‚Äôt think I had the power to change my experience.

Then one day, out of the blue, something unexpected happened: Heartbreak arrived at my door. Finally, I was ready to look into myself and find out what had led me to a place of such anguish. How could I turn this around?

In an effort to get answers to my questions, I studied psychotherapy, a process that would open up a whole new world of understanding for me about how we experience ourselves in relationships, and how we experience others. I was finally able to uncover the mystery behind why I found myself in a continuous cycle that began with excitement and hope and ended in disappointment and isolation. As a result, I can now live a purposeful life, in which I honour who I am. 
I set up this page to share with followers my insights into the behaviours that support mutually supportive and caring relationships. As part of this process, I will provide tools and resources that can be set into motion on the pathway to responsive relationship building. 
#honouringyourtrueself #relationships #selflove

We each have inherent value and worth. When we arrive in this world, we are beautiful, vulnerable beings full of wonder and awe.

However, once we are here, our conditioning causes us to lose faith in how truly loved, special and powerful we are. The messages we receive in our culture and society tell that certain parts of us are
unacceptable. We react to these messages by hiding the parts of ourselves that we no longer trust.

Each of us has a different story to tell, but somehow the theme is the same. When we are not regarded for who we really are, we become disconnected from our true selves. Consequently, we cannot believe that others can love us simply for who we are. Moreover, we do not understand why.

My first book ‚ÄúHonouring Your True Self‚Äù is an approach to honouring who you are so that you can belong in relationships that matter. It was
born out of my desire to uncover the behaviours that support a true emotional connection and bring into sharp focus the self-limiting behavioural patterns that prevent relationships from developing and growing. 
#honouringyourtrueself #loveyourself #intimacy #relationships
